Introduction: Data and Problem summary

For this project we were given a dataset composed of network features and activities with the goal of trying to understand what features classify an intrusion. We wanted to be able to classify these intrusions into different clusters to try and fully understand the attack vector. In this document you will see our process of exploring our data, predicting with our models, and then finally creating a narrative to explain the various intrusions we were able to detect in our dataset.

Predict using the tree and see its performance
include the ClassMetrics function in HW4
classMetrics <- function(score, y, cutoff, 
                         type = c("all", "accuracy", "sensitivity", 
                                  "specificity", "ppv", "npv", "precision", 
                                  "recall")) {

  # classify the observations based on score and cutoff
  hat.y <- ifelse(score < cutoff, 0, 1)
  
  # Form confusion matrix
  y = factor(y, levels = c("0","1"))
  hat.y = factor(hat.y, levels = c("0","1"))
  conf.mtrx = table(hat.y, y)
  
  # Use the appropriate entries in the confusion matrix to calculate all metrics:
  # accuracy, sensitivity, specificity, ppv, npv, precision (which is the same as ppv), recall (which is the same as sensitivity)
  accuracy = (conf.mtrx[1,1]+conf.mtrx[2,2])/sum(conf.mtrx)
  sensitivity = conf.mtrx[2,2]/sum(conf.mtrx[,2])
  specificity = conf.mtrx[1,1]/sum(conf.mtrx[,1])
  ppv = conf.mtrx[2,2]/sum(conf.mtrx[2,])
  npv = conf.mtrx[1,1]/sum(conf.mtrx[1,])
  precision = conf.mtrx[2,2]/sum(conf.mtrx[2,])
  recall = conf.mtrx[2,2]/sum(conf.mtrx[,2])
  
  # I'm giving you the exact names you should use in your output dataframe  
  metric.names <- c("accuracy", "sensitivity", "specificity", 
                    "ppv", "npv", "precision", "recall")

  # Form into data frame
  # Your data frame should contain ONLY ONE COLUMN named "value"
  # assign the metric.names above as the rownames of your data frame (just as the rownames, not as a second column!)
  res = data.frame(value = c(accuracy,sensitivity,specificity,ppv,npv,precision,recall), row.names = metric.names)
  
  # Return a list containing the confusion matrix and the data frame of the metrics
  # If "all", return all metrics. Otherwise, return just the requested subset of metrics
  if(type[1] == "all") {
    res = list(conf.mat = conf.mtrx, perf = res)
  } else {
    tem = data.frame(value = 1)
    i = 0
    for(item in type) {
      i = i+1
      tem[i,1] = res[item,"value"]
    }
    row.names(tem) <- type
    res = list(conf.mat = conf.mtrx, perf = tem)
  }
  res
}

  • Since we want to detect all intrusions, we want a high sensitivity instead of accuracy or specificity, ppv, etc.

  • The tree does a pretty good job on intrusion upsampling data that the sensitivity is 1.

  • The test accuracy of bagged tree is 0.9755, and sensitivity is 1. That estimate is directly equal to the outcome of our tree model, suggesting we may have found the optimal tree model in this random forest.We used an mtry value of 5 since the square root of 23 (our number of predictors) is about 4.8 so we rounded up to the nearest number, for the number of trees we stuck with the standard 500 trees.

We chose to run this on both our test set and our much larger random upsampled set to see how the the bagged random forest scaled. What we found was the accuracy decreased slightly to .9508, but sensitivity which in the case of network intrusions is the more important measure remained at 1.

The network intrusions data was imbalanced and heavily zero inflated so clustering it required a few tricks. The first is we converted categorical variables into factors and then into numerical variables. This was we could represent things like flag and have them weigh into our calculation. The values are not equal though, destination bytes and source bytes can be very large which throws off any estimate so we scaled our values. The training data also had to be upsampled in order to give representation to classes underrepresented. So we also added our initial training set mixed up to our upsampled set in an attempt to boost the number of low instance occurrences. To find the right value of k we ran k-means for all values of 1 through k up to 15. Our plot showed that the simplest model we performed best (lowest within sum of squares) with was when k was equal to 7 so we will use that mode l for our prediction. I added a plot to show the clusters, but since we are plotting in 7-dimensional space the cricle around the plot visualization didnt make sense.

Section 3: Key Findings and Main Takeaways

3.1 Key Findings - label prediction

Determine if it is possible to differentiate between the labeled intrusions and benign sessions.

  • Yes. We chose to use a decision tree to predict whether a session is intrusion or not. We upsampled and tried with a random forest as well and were able to predict accurately what was benign and what was not. While we did sometimes classify benign intrusions as harmful we did not classify harmful intrusions as benign and in case of network intrusions its more important to catch intrusions than not flag benign actors.

3.2 Identify different types of intrusions

Is it possible to identify different types of intrusions? If so, which values of which attributes in data correlate with the specific types of intrusions?

  • Yes. Here are the intrusions we discovered and their corresponding features which dictate their Intrusion Type classification.
  1. SYN Flooding Attack (Types 3, 4,and 7 - Type 7 appears to timeout or crash)

Description: A SYN flood attack consists on an attacker attempting to compromise a server by abusing the TCP handshake protocol. The attacker(client) sends as many SYN messages as possible to every open port on a server in an attempt to exhaust all of its available resources and rendering it useless. Typically the attacker will send only partial SYN messages or not send the response back to server in an attempt to not even engage the next steps of the handshake. These are typically used in conjunction with other attacks to wreck havoc.

Evidence: The flags RSTR, S0 and S3 lead to an intrusion 100% of the time. The S0 and S3 flags all are typical in a SYN flooding attack because these flags represent SYN messages with no acknowledgment.

  1. Buffer Overflow Attack (Attack Type 6)

Description: This attack occurs when an adversary overwhelms the FTP server by feeding in a very large input that the buffer cannot store gracefully. This can be used to overwrite or extract areas of memory.

Evidence: According to previous cluster prediction if the service is ftp/ftp_data, the duration is < 1537.5 && >= 529, and the src_bytes is >= 45304 then there was always an intrusion. We were able to locate this event in our data and 283618 bytes were sent via ftp_data most likely to overwhelm the buffer.

  1. Man in the Middle Attack or UDP Flood (MITM) (Attack Type 1)

Description: A man in the middle attack is basically when an attacker sits between a client and a trusted source. The attacker can either pose as the trusted source or eavesdrop on the communication. Trusted sites typically will use a certificate to authenticate its security. Attackers can sometimes spoof these certificates in order to pose as a more trusted source.

Evidence: We think there is evidence to suggest that the attacker has been able to spoof a certificate on this network. From our cluster we can see that every instance that uses a private (HTTPS) connection leads to an intrusion.

  1. FTP Anonymous Login Attack (Attack Type = 5, Type 2)

Description: This attack is successful when an organization has not properly configured their FTP settings. Some FTP servers allow for anonymous login, this means that anyone who uses the default anoymous:anoymous login credentials will have access to the FTP server.

Evidence: Our tree from earlier showed us that 100% of the time if the dst_bytes >= 157.5 and duration >= 277 then is_intrusion = 1. Knowing this, in our data we were able to discover a grouping of ftp connections being made with the dist_bytes = 160 and the duration = 280. Additionally, all of these connections also had logged_in = 1 and guest_login = 1, this is evidence that these particular events in the data are related to a FTP Anonymous Login attack.

3.3 Detecting System

  • Develop and implement a systematic approach to detect instances of intrusions in log files. Your system will need to be able to take a new network_traffic log file and determine the existence of known patterns of intrusions as well as anomalies which may be indicative of new and unknown intrusion patterns.

3.4 Evaluate detection power of the system.

Input:

Argument Description
file the name of the new log file(name.csv)make sure its under working directory
cluster.tree a rpart tree object to predict clusters, use intrusion.cluster.tree as default

Output:

The output will be a list containing the following elements

Argument Description 
detectSystem <- function(file, intrusion.tree = intrusion.tree, intrusion.cluster.tree = intrusion.cluster.tree,
                         flag.table = flag.table, protocol.table = protocol.table, service.table = service.table) {
  
  set.seed(456)
  
  # data processing
  # load the new log file (If detect in real-time, read the updated line)
  traffic <- read.csv(file)
  # clean the data : remove NA

  traffic <- na.omit(traffic)
  
  # intrusion prediction
  pred_intrusion <- predict(intrusion.tree, newdata = traffic, type = "class")
  pred_intrusion <- data.frame(pred_intrusion = pred_intrusion)
  
  # add a new column `pred_intrusion`
  traffic <- cbind(traffic, pred_intrusion)
  
  # prediction == 1 data set
  intru.pred.true <- traffic[traffic$pred_intrusion == 1,]
  
  if(is.null(intru.pred.true)) {
    potential_intru = FALSE
  } else {
    potential_intru = TRUE
  }

  # assume no unknown intrusion types existing
  new_cluster = FALSE
  if(potential_intru) {
    # the cluster tree can only fit existing factors
    intru.true.merge = merge(intru.pred.true, flag.table, by.x = "flag", by.y = "name" , all = TRUE, sort = FALSE)
    intru.true.merge = merge(intru.true.merge, protocol.table, 
                             by.x = "protocol_type", by.y = "name" , all = TRUE, sort = FALSE)
    intru.true.merge = merge(intru.true.merge, service.table, 
                             by.x = "service", by.y = "name" , all = TRUE, sort = FALSE)
    
    # find out if there is unknown intrusion type
    if(anyNA(intru.true.merge)) {
      new_cluster = TRUE
      intru.true.clean = na.omit(intru.true.merge)
    
    } else {
      intru.true.clean = intru.true.merge
    }
    # clusters prediction
    intru.cluster.pred = predict(intrusion.cluster.tree, newdata = intru.true.clean, type = "class")
    intru_clusters = summary(intru.cluster.pred)
  }
  
  
  res = list(potential_intru = potential_intru, new_cluster = new_cluster, intru_clusters = intru_clusters)
  res
}

                   protocol.table = protocol.table, service.table = service.table)

3.5 Real-time detection & information exchanges

  • Can your intrusion detector be used in real-time? It would need to be able to receive data about a current session, and in seconds determine if it is likely to be and intrusion of previously seen type or an anomaly potentially signifying an unseen yet intrusion mode. What information should be exchanged via the user interface of such system?

Yes, we are able to detect from information on a current session if a session is an intrusion or not. There are 10 fields on a user interface that would be relevant. They are the dst bytes, src bytes, duration, service, flag, login status, guest login status, hot indicators, and the protocol type. However these are not all equally important, duration, flag, dst bytes, service, and source bytes are most important.

We can also tell whether an intrusion is an anomaly by predicting whether or not the new data is an intrusion and checking if any row values differ from our established types.
